column8: Classify non-graphic violence (fights, chases, implied injury, threats) with no detailed gore. Distinguish safety training or news reporting from entertainment and glorification. Output JSON schema.
column15: Detect fights, punches, kicks, weapons shown without blood, police chases, non-gory accidents, animated violence. Contact sports that look like street fights treated as violence, not sports. Apply stricter gating for <10 while often allowing teens. Output visual JSON schema.
column16: Detect talk of fighting, threats ('I'll kill you', 'beat you up'), violent roleplay, and non-graphic crime descriptions. Separate game trash-talk from serious threats but still lower safety for younger kids. Fill audio JSON.

column15: Detect rings, mats, referees, uniforms, scoreboards to recognize organized sports (WWE, boxing) versus unsupervised street fights. Mark as sports-violence and set <10 to Block, 10-13 Gate, older teens Allow unless blood/injury is extreme. Output visual JSON.
column16: From commentary ('what a punch', 'knockout!') and crowd sounds, recognize organized sports vs real assault. Sports commentary is safer but still intense for young kids. Apply the sports rule for age bands in audio JSON.

column16: Detect scary sound design, screams, whispers, horror narration, paranormal stories. Assess intensity of fear and disturbing themes. Block <10, Gate 10-13, teens as Gate/Allow depending on severity. Output audio JSON.
